## Rationalizations to Reject

These are common excuses that open gaps. Reject them all:

| Rationalization | Why it's false |
|---|---|
| "It's just a development default" | If it reaches production code, it's a vulnerability |
| "The prod config overrides it" | Prove it with a code trace; many apps fail silently |
| "It will never run without config" | Prove it. Defensive code > optimistic assumptions |
| "It's behind authentication" | Defense in depth; a compromised session still exploits weak defaults |
| "We'll fix it before release" | Document and fix it now; "later" rarely arrives |
| "The information is public anyway" | A metadata leak can be used for reconnaissance |

---

## RLS on Supabase — Mandatory Rule

When the project uses Supabase, **always** validate that RLS policies are created for all tables with sensitive or multi-tenant data.

When starting work on a Supabase project, use the Supabase MCP to check the current state of the policies. If you identify tables without adequate policies, propose creating them considering:

- Existing user roles (anonymous, authenticated, admin)
- The multi-tenancy model (per user, per organization, hybrid)
- Operations allowed per role and table (SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE)
- The column that identifies the owner or tenant of the record

RLS policies are the last line of defense against data leakage between tenants. The absence of RLS allows malformed queries or injection attacks to access unauthorized data, even if the application filters correctly.
